2026-03-27 | Check Matrix After K Cyclic Row Shifts

	Question
Return true if after k operations matrix becomes identical to original.

	Approach
1.	Key Observation:
		Shifting k times = shifting (k % n) times  
		where n = number of columns  

2.	For each row:
		- Even row → left shift by k % n  
		- Odd row → right shift by k % n  

3.	Instead of modifying matrix:
		Compare positions directly.

4.	For each cell (i, j):
		find where it came from:
		
		If even row:
			original index = (j + k) % n  
		If odd row:
			original index = (j - k + n) % n  

5.	If any mismatch → return false  
6.	If all match → return true  

	Time Complexity
	O(m × n)

	Space Complexity
	O(1)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    bool areSimilar(vector<vector<int>>& mat, int k) {

        int m = mat.size();
        int n = mat[0].size();

        k %= n;

        for(int i=0;i<m;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<n;j++){

                int originalIndex;

                if(i % 2 == 0){
                    originalIndex = (j + k) % n;
                } else {
                    originalIndex = (j - k + n) % n;
                }

                if(mat[i][j] != mat[i][originalIndex])
                    return false;
            }
        }

        return true;
    }
};

	Key Insight
After n shifts, rows return to original state.  
So only **k % n** matters.  

Instead of simulating shifts,
we directly check if each element matches its expected original position.
